<ol class="no-markers" start="4">
<li dir="ltr">
<h2 id="risks-and-limitations">Risks and Limitations of Copy Trading</h2>
</li>
</ol>
<p dir="ltr">Copy trading in itself does not eliminate the various risks that exist in the market. It is important that those using this service as a passive investment understand the risks that copy trading can pose to their accounts.</p>
<ol class="no-markers">
<li dir="ltr">
<h3 dir="ltr">Lack of Control</h3>
</li>
</ol>
<p>One of the risks of copy trading to Followers is that they do not have complete control of their trades once they have signed up for the service. They are at the absolute mercy of the Followers whose trades they are copying. If a Follower suddenly turns unprofitable and loses ten trades in a row, the same results are replicated on the Follower&#8217;s account.</p>
<p>All elements of the Provider&#8217;s trades are copied: risk exposure size, entry and exit prices. If a Provider is risking more than the recommended 5% of his account size in trades, the same measure of risk is applied to the Follower&#8217;s account. If the Provider uses risk-reward ratios that do not conform to acceptable risk management standards, the same ratios are applied to the Follower&#8217;s account.</p>
<p>Since the Follower cannot set their stop loss or take profit levels, they are entirely vulnerable to any poor judgments and trading decisions of the Provider. The only way to prevent this is to unsubscribe from the Provider&#8217;s trades completely. Any subscriptions are not usually refunded, so you must choose your trade Providers carefully.</p>
<ol class="no-markers" start="2">
<li dir="ltr">
<h3 dir="ltr">Over-Reliance on Signal Providers</h3>
</li>
</ol>
<p dir="ltr">Copy trading makes the Follower dependent on the Provider. The ATFX CopyTrade platform only presents the opportunity. It is your job as a trader to select the Provider to follow. If you choose wrongly, everything else will follow suit. If you cannot use the trading metrics and statistics of the Providers at your disposal to make an informed choice of whose trades to copy to avoid finding yourself in hot waters.</p>
<p dir="ltr">This over-reliance on signal/trade providers has its merits and demerits. Suppose you depend 100% on the trades provided by the trader you follow, and you cannot detect changes in strategy or market conditions that may pose a risk to profitable outcomes. In that case, you will have problems along the way. The lesson here is not to rely too much on signal providers. It pays to have some knowledge so you know when to disable the copied trades from a faltering Provider or when to choose another Provider entirely.</p>
<ol class="no-markers" start="3">
<li dir="ltr">
<h3 dir="ltr">Risk of Fraud and Scams</h3>
</li>
</ol>
<p dir="ltr">Any industry or sector with high financial turnover will surely attract the bad guys. Forex is not immune to scams, so do not expect any less from the copy-trading industry. You must know how to protect yourself from the common scams within the copy-trading industry.</p>
<p dir="ltr">What kind of scams can occur in copy trading?</p>
<ul>
<li dir="ltr">
<p dir="ltr">Misrepresentation of trade results by fraudulent signal providers. Some signals providers have found ways of deleting a bad run of results so it does not show up in their trade history.</p>
</li>
<li dir="ltr">
<p dir="ltr">Manipulation of market inefficiencies.</p>
</li>
<li dir="ltr">
<p dir="ltr">Posting unusually high trade returns without highlighting the serious risk involved is a practice that paints a one-sided picture of what can happen in the market if unduly high risk is used. Some Providers use a lucky run of results as the source of their trade history.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p dir="ltr">Traders should also be wary of Providers with unusually high returns without other metrics backing up these returns. You may end up subscribing to the services of a Provider who has thrown risk management to the dogs, and you could lose your money very quickly.</p>
<ol class="no-markers" start="4">
<li dir="ltr">
<h3 dir="ltr">Market Risk</h3>
</li>
</ol>
<p dir="ltr">What are market risks? Market risks are events in the forex market that can lead to sudden and unexpected capital loss. These risk events include news trades, slippage, and other events beyond human control, such as natural disasters, outbreaks of war, a global pandemic, or terrorist attacks with global ramifications.</p>
<p dir="ltr">Several examples of such risk events have occurred in the last twenty years. Copy trading does not protect the trader from or eliminate market risks.</p>
<ol class="no-markers">
<li dir="ltr">
<p dir="ltr">9/11 terrorist attacks on several targets in the US on 11 September 2001 caused a severe market upheaval that struck several financial markets.</p>
</li>
<li dir="ltr">
<p dir="ltr">The 15 January 2015 de-pegging of the Swiss Franc from the Euro by the Swiss National Bank.</p>
</li>
<li dir="ltr">
<p dir="ltr">The earthquake in Christchurch, New Zealand, in 2011 caused a massive safe-haven demand and strengthening of the Japanese Yen, necessitating intervention by the Bank of Japan.</p>
</li>
<li dir="ltr">
<p dir="ltr">The unexpected premarket interest rate cut by the Federal Reserve on 22 January 2008.</p>
</li>
<li dir="ltr">
<p dir="ltr">The sudden outbreak of the Libyan civil war in 2011</p>
</li>
<li dir="ltr">
<p dir="ltr">The outbreak of the COVID-19 pandemic in March 2020. This also led to several unscheduled and unexpected interest rate cuts by global central banks, creating a massive shock in the currency markets.</p>
</li>
</ol>
<p dir="ltr">If you have any active trades placed on your account via a copy trading portal, you will be exposed and could suffer devastating losses. These market risk events are usually unexpected and cause severe market shocks. They typically cause slippage, which overwhelms the ability of brokers or counterparties to honor pre-set stop loss settings.</p>
<p dir="ltr">It will help if you remember that such events can occur and you can protect yourself as much as you can for such times.</p>
<ol class="no-markers" start="5">
<li dir="ltr">
<h3 dir="ltr">Lack of Customization</h3>
</li>
</ol>
<p>Copy trading has sometimes been likened to a master-slave relationship, though not in the strict sense. Anything the Provider does regarding trading reflects on the Follower&#8217;s account without the latter&#8217;s input. The Follower has no say in the trade process or trade outcome, which means that the Follower cannot perform any form of customization.</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="size-full wp-image-46232 aligncenter" src="https://www.atfx.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/02/ATCopy-tradestats.jpg" alt="ATCopy-tradestats" width="907" height="607" srcset="https://www.atfx.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/02/ATCopy-tradestats.jpg 907w, https://www.atfx.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/02/ATCopy-tradestats-300x201.jpg 300w, https://www.atfx.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/02/ATCopy-tradestats-768x514.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 907px) 100vw, 907px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Trade Statistics for a Provider</strong></p>
<p>It is impossible to adjust the Provider&#8217;s trading style to match the risk preferences of the Follower. You cannot choose what assets the Provider trades or change the Provider&#8217;s trading style to match your preferences. So you are forced to accept every element of the Provider&#8217;s trading behaviour.</p>
<p>If a Provider gets too emotional on a particular trading day and starts to make trading errors, the best the Follower can do is to unfollow that Provider completely. There is no chance of a refund in such circumstances. This is why you must consider your individual needs and only select a Provider who can match your preferences with their risk management, trading style, and overall performance.</p>
